# PWA + iOS 26 Frontend Guardrails

When changing frontend code in this project, prioritize resilient iPhone PWA behavior (especially Dynamic Island/notch devices).

## Safe Areas and Header Positioning

- Always protect top UI with safe-area insets: use `env(safe-area-inset-top)` and existing safe utilities (`pt-safe-ios`, `pl-safe`, `pr-safe`, `pb-safe`).
- For mobile headers, avoid shorthand that can override safe area (avoid `p-*` with safe top); prefer explicit `px-* pb-* pt-safe-ios`.
- Keep top bars visually clear of notch/Dynamic Island even during route transitions and scroll restore.

## Viewport and Scrolling

- Prefer dynamic viewport units for app shells (`100dvh` with `100svh` fallback), not only `100vh`/`h-screen`.
- Ensure PWA layouts keep independent scroll containers stable on iOS (no content hidden under top/bottom system areas).
- Preserve bottom navigation clearance with safe-area-aware padding.

## PWA Metadata and Platform Support

- Keep `viewport-fit=cover` enabled for standalone PWA layouts.
- Preserve Apple web app metadata (`appleWebApp`, icons, status bar settings) when editing layout/metadata files.
- Do not remove manifest/offline hooks without validating standalone install behavior on iPhone.

## Change Quality Bar

- When touching layout/header/navigation, verify both current and legacy frontend shells that might still render on some routes.
- Prefer shared utilities over one-off per-page fixes so iOS behavior is consistent across app screens.
- If a proposed UI change can overlap with notch/safe areas, proactively include safe-area and viewport handling in the same PR.
